segments.text: Okay.
You ready?
Yeah.
Okay.
Morning, Chief Luther.
As you know, this morning I'm going to ask you a few questions about the community.
Yes, sir.
And just answer any way you want to.
Okay.
The first question will be, Chief Luther, when and where were you born?
In Frost, actually, September 4, 1916.
Okay, what about... That's a small community in, uh, Navarre County, near Corse County.
In Corse County.
Mm-hmm.
Okay, and did your family live there long?
Yes, uh-huh, for, um, some, uh, 50, 50 years.
50 to 60 years.
Mm-hmm.
Okay, and where did you receive your early schooling?
At Forster County High School.
Forster County High School, and like I said, junior high?
Junior high, elementary, junior high, and then junior high.
Junior high, okay.
What were your plans after graduation?
Did you have some kind of degree, or excuse me, I mean some kind of career in mind after graduating?
Not necessarily.
My ambition at that particular time was becoming a professional baseball player, which I had a bright chance of playing in the Class B league with Tyler Texas.
Yes, I see.
Is that pro?
Pro, yes, sir.
I mean, you could go straight from high school to pro without going to college.
Yes, I see.
Okay.
Do you have anything else in mind?
Or is that just the overwhelming ambition?
Yes, that was my main ambition.
And my second ambition was to be a member of the Department of Public Safety.
Okay.
Now we'll get on to the College Station.
When and what brought you first to the College Station in Bryan area?
In 1942, I was employed by the DPS as a Texas Highway Patrolman.
First station was in Waco.
There until March of 1944, went into service, U.S. Navy.
Spent two years with this charge in March of 1946, at which time I was reinstated as a Texas Highway Patrolman and sent to Bryce.
So you came out of the Navy and went back into the DPS and you were assigned here at College Station.
Yes, assigned to Bryan Station, Bryan College Station Community.
Was that during World War II?
That was after World War II.
So the two years you served was during World War II?
During World War II, yes.
Do you remember what year this was?
Okay.
Now, what are your earliest memories of this area as you came back?
A community-like city.
Bryan, at that time, had a population of some 13,000, 13,500 people.
And at that particular time, College Station had a population of some 35,000 to 37,000.
Was it densely populated?
No, sir.
Was it flat plains here?
Yes.
There we go.
As a matter of fact, Texas Avenue, that took the time to clean Brian and College Station.
It was an 18-foot slab with a gravel trail.
I see.
I'm I'm just I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm I'm
I didn't realize it was that distance in between them.
Okay.
Now, where was the major part of College Station located when you came here?
I'm not sure, you know, where it was.
I was wondering if it was located in one particular section or was it surrounding?
The North Gate was the major part.
Then everything was located on North Dade?
Generally, yes sir.
I thought there might have been an old section over here on the South Dade side.
That was partially populated on the South side at that time.
You're talking about the old Hardwick?
It was a place.
Oh, there was nightclubs over there?
I see.
And there was just a very few houses and most of everything was located over here at Northgate.
Most of the business was there.
As a matter of fact, there was a few business establishments over on Texas Avenue.
Jones Pharmacy is the one that I remember rewetting.
Was there anything back here on the east side, you know, like across the tracks?
Did the school take up all the way to the tracks?
To the tracks.
Was there anything on the other side?
They've got some buildings over there now.
Uh, the old cattle farm, right?
Yes, sir.
And, uh, and dairy farm.
Uh-huh.
I see.
Okay.
Um, uh, this is probably a little bit, maybe a little tougher of a question.
Uh, since then, how has the area expanded?
Which way has it, which way has it gone?
It's gone in all directions.
Yes, sir.
Both, uh, the City of Bryan and Copper State.
Yes, sir.
It didn't really matter, just the whole thing exploded?
Yes, just exploded.
In all directions.
Which way do you think it came to that?
That's a hard answer.
It appears that Bryan, perhaps, will have to go east, and perhaps College Station.
College Station will have to go east, or south of east.
You have me know if College Station and Bryan people have always got along together good?
Yes, very well as far as I know.
work together and projects.
Yes, coordinated all of that.
Are there any, to your knowledge, are there any parades that have been going on?
Year after year, it's kind of like an annual celebration?
Yes, the Christmas parade is an annual
celebration, and that's on November.
And when does that take place?
Usually around the first of December.
First of December.
And who participates?
Both College Station and Bryan, and some of the surrounding communities.
Can you remember anyone in particular that was kind of
and uh... they have a
Okay.
Let's turn to farming.
This area is a lot of farming, concerned with the farming lot.
Can you tell me, has there been, to the best of your knowledge, any changes in farming, the way they do farming, the tools?
Yes, it's become mechanized.
Can you tell me about that this year?

Yes, when I first came to Brian, it was not uncommon to see mules and horses used in cultivating the land in the private river bottom, but now it's all mechanized and tractors and mechanical equipment, and that's definitely some of the tractors they're using, atro-stock, or when they're using the mules.
What was that saying?
uh... eight-year-old rather than too so they uh...
techniques other than increasing the amount of area they can form at one time?
Like crop rotation, like using big tractors.
Remember the ones with the air conditioning they've got now?
Yes, uh-huh.
Are there any other techniques?
None that I know of.
I think it's more or less a seasonal type.
Those two crops have always been major?
Yes.
Would you happen to know
when irrigation became widely used in this area?
I think perhaps in about 1957 or long about that period.
Is there anything that made it mandatory then or it's just what caused it to come in?
I think the farmers at that time, I don't know, in 50, maybe 55,
Okay, now I guess everybody, all the farmers in the area generally went to it automatically.
Yes.
Okay, please describe, if you would, what forms of recreation
everyone july first-year yes anything that everybody else here
You know, a lot of people like to go out to Somerville.
Well, of course, yes, but there was an old facility at Somerville in 1964, or by 1964.
Is that a, I'm sorry, I probably heard, is that a,
A man-made lake?
A man-made.
When was it made?
Let me clarify that.
You mean by man-made, of course, it was the construction of the dam up in the middle of the land in the Yehaw Creek area.
So it wouldn't be until 1964 that it would be used?
That's right.
Okay.
Was there anything else that everyone liked to do?
Was there a few bars or something?
Oh yes, there were quite a few bars and a nightclub.
Oh, a rink, I see.
Was it the same one that's located over there?
No, this one was located on Highway 21, some mile after mile after mile.
Where did everybody seem to go on Friday afternoons?
For us, Friday afternoon we may go to Somerville.
On a particular night we may go to Lakeview.
Is there any particular place that everybody seemed to really enjoy and stood out in everybody's mind?
Oh, man, I can't think of any.
One place.
Okay.
Where did you like to go?
Did you have one particular place that you enjoyed?
During the weekends, we would go to the night owls.
Friday, Saturday, and Sunday, so I didn't have an opportunity to visit or go to too many places.
You were off probably during the week.
Yeah, one day a week.
I'd usually be on Wednesday.
And then we would start to get to college during the day off.
And I spent many hours working in the day.
Did you start playing in the College Station area?
College Station, yeah.
You would never get caught outside of the area?
Oh, yes.
We had an area assigned to us.
At that time, we patrolled from Bryan to the Paris County CBX and Highway 6 and Highway 2 Main.
We had all the Bunnison County.
We had all the Robertson County and all the Madison County.
Three or fifty weeks?
Three.
Wouldn't be the same way as that?
No.
Now they have some twelve uniformed police officers, DPS officers stationed in this area.
And three or four in Kyle, and three or four in Hearn, and the same number in Madisonville, and about the same number in Madisonville and Hicksville.
Were there any local police in those areas that you had gone?
Yes, very few.
Very few.
When I first formed Brian, the senior college station had one police force.
And Brian had some total of seven or eight, not more than ten.
My goodness.
Was there enough crime to keep them busy, or did they need more people but they couldn't get them, or was it just a quiet time?
Well, they were always needing more people.
I mean, it's a real-ass community.
It's not too incriminating.
Okay.
Then, traffic was a major problem.
How was the traffic in the first county?
Well, when I first came to Bride, in Bride's County, the year of 1946, there were 14,000 people.
Now, we have some 48,000 people.
I'm sure I'm not real sure about things weren't all the roads paved
No.
We had the old farm 16... What is that?
It was out of paid road.
We had a farm that was out of road.
and north of Bryan, and northwest of Bryan, but that's not a paved road.
And that's the only thing that was paved in the way that that took the time.
Even the old San Antonio OS office, I think that was, was not all paved.
And about the only paved roads that I can remember are Highway 6 and Highway 9.
Uh, I was just thinking about lights.
When did they put up the traffic lights?
They haven't always been there.
They were always up there.
No, it is.
The lights between, uh, uh, Bryan and, uh, Tyler's Station have been recently installed.
I don't remember what it was called.
Uh...
That's been very recent.
Before then, it was, what, just, you just came to a turn and stopped?
Yeah, stopped, stopped.
Stopped?
Stopped.
It's been traffics, or was it traffic accidents that made you concerned right then before the lights went off?
Mm-hmm.
Can you recall any natural disasters such as floods or droughts or even epidemics that have hit this area since you've been here?
No epidemics, but I can remember two floods.
I believe one in 1907, the rise of the river, and then in 1965, I believe.
Was it a hurricane, or was it weather coming from the north?
Yeah, just heavy rainfall in the North Texas area, around Waco, Clifton, and the areas of the general area of the Brighton River, or the watershed that goes into the Brighton River.
Oh, I see.
It rained up north and flowed downstream to us here and flooded us through.

Of course, with heavy rains here also, rivers, the Navasota River, would have contributed in the fact, you know, big rains around the head, and the rains in general, big rains in general, over central.
And you can only remember about two little areas.
That's all that I can remember of.
Yes, sir.
Okay, how about grouse?
Well, the one I believe in 57 that I mentioned a while ago, I think that can be considered a grouse.
How long did that last?
Do you remember?
About a year.
It lasted a whole year.
Well, not necessarily, but not enough rainfall during that period to break it.
How did that affect the farmers?
Did they all go bankrupt?
Did they sue its crops?
No.
They brought out the irrigation.
They brought out the irrigation and perhaps had a little money to, or borrowed money to take care of it.
They lost it for about 50 years.
Are there any legends or tall tales about this area?
Where I'm from, you might hear a few tall tales about the woods.
And I was just wondering if there's any legends or tall tales about this area.
There might not.
I'm sure there are, but I don't know.
Okay.
Now, looking back over the years that you've been here, have the people changed much?
Not a great figure.
They were the back end that was in the community.
That's true.
Were they more aggressive?
Framelier or anything like that?
No, I don't think so.
This is always, in my opinion, the real framer community.
Both Brian and Polly
What is it about College Station that has kept you here?
It couldn't be just a job, as you've already said.
You really like it.
Yes.
Well, we mentioned the good people and the idea of ladies.
And my primary purpose when I first came to Bryan and the college basement for me to stay was that I had two sons who I wanted one day to graduate from A&M University.
Of course, at that time it was Texas A&M College.
That was my comfortable reason for staying in this family for thirty years without me.
Did both sons finally go to Texas A&M?
Yes, my oldest son left for four years and passed for a device.
Then he came to the University of, I don't know, the University of
and graduated from Harvard in 1967.
Oh my goodness, you know all of them.
Yeah, and my young son, Gene, attended Allen Academy, too.
Then, one year at A&M, and then classed for the Pan American University Baseball College.
Mm-hmm, I see.
What is it that's keeping you here now today?
Did you put your roots here for thirty years and they're not often ready?
That's true.
It's the same thing.
It's the community in mind.
And the people that I know and my good friends and...

Still in law enforcement, so to speak, it's the plus 100% cooperation that we get, or this department gets, from the Department of Public Safety, the Goddard Station PD, the Brown PD, and the Brown Sheriff Department.
But as a matter of fact, all law enforcement agencies, all over,
Is that usually the general consensus of people that you've met passing through, that they've been surprised and happy about College Station being such a nice place?
Yes.
Okay.
Chief Luther, I'd like to thank you very much for giving me this time to interview you.
I've enjoyed it and learned a great deal.
Thank you, sir.
I've enjoyed it very much.
Appreciate you coming by.
Yes, sir.
I hope I've done a halfway decent job.
